<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / Union leaders 'support end to block vote'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIX out of 10 union leaders would support abolition of the union block vote
at Labour party conferences, according to a survey disclosed yest-erday.
The results will hearten party members who want a fundamental reappraisal of
Labour's links with the unions.
Until now senior union leaders have expressed caution about the depth of
reforms due to be implemented by next year's Labour conference.
The survey in New Statesman and Society magazine also indicated that eight
out of 10 union leaders would support the introduction of a
one-member-one-vote system for the selection of Labour parliamentary
candidates.
Three quarters would back one-member-one-vote for the election of the Labour
leader.
The magazine pointed out that support for abolition of the block vote does
not translate into backing for the abolition of party-union links.
One of the respondents in the survey who backed abolition added: 'We need a
reputable link mechanism before abolition.'
One possible solution - the automatic conversion of members of unions which
pay a political levy to Labour into individual party members - was backed by
three out of 10 union leaders. But some respondents argued strongly that
union members wishing to become party members should pay the full individual
membership fee.
In a series of questions on how union leaders rate shadow cabinet members,
Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, came first above Mr John Smith, party
leader. Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, was third and Mr Robin Cook,
shadow trade and industry secretary, fourth. In last year's poll Mr Smith
came first.
The New Statesman said it seemed that the Labour leader had already begun to
exhaust his honeymoon period.
Questionnaires were sent to 100 union leaders and 36 were completed.
Unions seek illumination, Page 19
