<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / Hour of reckoning for training schemes: Pressures on
ministers responsible for programmes for the jobless
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MRS Gillian Shephard, employment secretary, will today begin receiving
submissions to her wide-ranging review of government programmes for the
adult unemployed.
Under review is the ET scheme itself as well as Employment Action, the
benefit-plus-temporary-work scheme for the long-term unemployed, and
Jobclubs.
Mrs Shephard is likely to be constrained by political and financial
pressures. She will face calls from Tory backbenchers who want to follow the
US example of Workfare under which the long-term unemployed receive benefit
only if they undertake community work.
Civil servants believe it would be difficult to run sufficient Workfare
schemes to mop up the large numbers of people eligible.
It is understood that the government has similarly been backing away from
the proposal to cut entitlement to unemployment benefit from one year to six
months.
Training providers hope the review will concentrate on quality in order to
equip the UK for any upturn in the economy.
But the Department of Employment - like others in Whitehall - is likely to
be subject to funding cuts in the current Public Expenditure Survey.
ET will be the most vulnerable scheme because the other main training
programme, Youth Training - the scheme for those aged 16 to 18 - guarantees
a place to all who want one. It is politically important for the government
that this is met. ET carries no such formal guarantee.
ET is criticised as ripe for reform. Started in 1988, before the recession,
its clients are mainly low-skill individuals, and 47 per cent are inner-city
residents who worked in the old manufacturing industries. About 104,000
people are doing ET in England and Wales.
The scheme's record is poor. Only 36 per cent of those completing schemes go
into jobs, self employment or full - time training and about 30 per cent get
a qualification.
Many of its clients view ET as a government device to get them off the
unemployment register, while many training providers claim they are unable
to give quality training because the Pounds 800m-a-year scheme is
underfunded.
The Unemployment Unit, a research organisation, said that while job entry
rates could be explained partly by the weakness of regional employment
conditions, qualification rates reflected the poor quality of training.
The 82 Training and Enterprise Councils (Tecs) which administer government
funded training schemes in England and Wales want a freer hand in who they
can train on ET schemes.
In their submission to Mrs Shephard they are expected to point to a range of
alternatives, such as varying periods of training for different groups
depending on their needs. Short intensive courses could assist skilled
individuals recently made unemployed. More disadvantaged people could have
longer training.
Last week G10, the group of 10 Tec chairmen who represent the views of Tecs
to government, made it clear that further cuts to their training budgets
were unacceptable. It is likely, however, that if asked to make funding
choices they would opt to have fewer people trained, but to a higher
quality.
Mr Stuart Bishell, managing director of Astra Training, the largest provider
of ET training, said: 'We want the focus of government spending on training
to be on those people who are most likely to benefit from it most rapidly.'
Such a move is being considered by the Department of Employment. Mrs
Shephard could argue that the Treasury should allow Tecs greater freedom of
choice in return for cash constraints, and allow her department to negotiate
targets. Tecs could for example be paid varying amounts for training
different groups.
But the Treasury wants the rules on ET eligibility tightened, not relaxed.
At present Tecs are allowed only to put other groups on ET after satisfying
demand from the long-term unemployed.
Another option being considered is expanding Employment Action. Set up a
year ago, EA is cheaper than ET but has not been a great success. About
23,000 out of 30,000 places are filled. Whether this scheme could be
expanded without some element of compulsion is debatable.
Tecs would certainly like greater ability to mix and match programmes to
meet the needs of their catchment areas - but not if that means less funding
for training. It is a demand that government will find hard to meet.
</TEXT>
