<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / Big battalions improve finances
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST of the largest trade unions improved their financial position last
year, according to a survey by the Labour Research Department, a union
research organisation.
The survey found many unions had taken steps to reverse financial declines,
but the LRD warned the situation was still precarious.
A number of new pressures faced unions, including the government's
forthcoming legislation on the 'check-off' system of members paying union
contributions.
The proposed law will require members regularly to re-authorise their
payments. LRD said this could increase the likelihood of 'disaffected or
disorganised members dropping out'.
Finances of most of the unions affiliated to the Trades Union Congress
worsened in the late 1980s for several reasons, including falling
membership. The TUC warned last year that 'the maintenance of effective
control of expenditure must remain a major priority'. The LRD found
membership generally fell again last year, but most unions increased their
dues.
Six of the biggest 10 unions performed better last year than in 1990. These
were Nalgo, Nupe and Cohse, the public service unions; the GMB general
union; MSF, the manufacturing, science and finance union; and Usdaw, the
shopworkers union. All produced a surplus on income and expenditure. Only
Nupe and Usdaw produced a surplus in 1990.
The biggest deficit of Pounds 12.4m was incurred by the TGWU general union.
The union said yesterday that it believed it had turned the corner by
cutting staff and raising dues.
Ninety large companies have paid 227 departing directors a total of nearly
Pounds 33m over the past 18 months, according to the LRD.
The LRD survey of companies paying out 'golden handshakes' worth more than
Pounds 100,000 showed an average pay-out of Pounds 144,720. At least nine
directors received more than Pounds 400,000 each.
A similar survey last year found 85 companies paid 186 directors a total of
Pounds 25.1m, an average pay-off of Pounds 135,079.
Sometimes golden handshakes had riders on them, said the LRD, with
agreements by the recipients not to work for main competitors for a period
of time.
The LRD is proposing that the rules governing disclosure of company
financial information on such payouts needed tightening as the majority of
company accounts did not detail payments to individual directors.
Labour Research, September 1992. LRD, 78 Blackfriars Road, London SE1 8HF.
Pounds 2.25.
</TEXT>
