FT  04 SEP 92 / Lib Dems seek UN reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UNITED Nations should be given the power to intervene in countries'
domestic affairs, the Liberal Democrats said yesterday in proposals for
wide-ranging reform of the UN.
Sir David Steel, the party's foreign affairs spokesman, said the criticisms
made of the UN over its role in the former Yugoslavia and in Somalia
reflected the unwillingness of the international community to consider
changes to nations' attitudes to sovereignty following the end of the cold
war.
'The UN as an organisation has never lived up to the dreams of its founders
nor to its charter,' he said at the launch of Beyond The Nation State, a
document to be discussed at the party's annual conference later this month.
The paper envisages the more systematic development of a range of sanctions
against countries which breach criteria on, for instance, human rights, the
right to peaceful co-existence of nations and the environment. The UN is
urged to improve its information gathering and set up a permanent
peacekeeping force.
