<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / Users warn on N-power levy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LARGE energy users warned yesterday that proposals to reduce the Pounds
1.2bn nuclear levy on electricity bills would not be substantial enough or
speedy enough to solve the problems facing industry.
Mr Mike Brogden, chief executive of ICI Chemicals and Polymers, said he was
encouraged that the industry regulator Offer and the generator PowerGen -
both of which have called this week for a cut in the levy - accepted that
power prices were uncompetitive.
He said: 'However, I am also disappointed that the solution being proposed
is far too small, and on a timescale which will not solve the serious
problem on energy costs.'
The 11 per cent levy was imposed on all electricity bills after the
privatisation of the fossil-fuel generators to subsidise the higher costs of
other sources of electricity. More than 95 per cent of the levy goes to
Nuclear Electric, the state-owned generator.
Mr Brogden has told Offer and the Department of Trade and Industry that
ICI's chlor-alkali business on Merseyside, which is one of the biggest
consumers of electricity in the UK. has faced increases in electricity costs
of almost 60 per cent since April last year.
This had made it increasingly uncompetitive with producers in Europe and
North America, and had brought cuts in production.
Mr Ian Blakey, chairman of the Energy Intensive Users Group, said he was
pleased that Offer was 'prepared to listen'. He said, however, that a
reduction in the nuclear levy did not go far enough and industry should be
the principal beneficiary of any reduction in prices.
</TEXT>
