<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / Shipbuilder to shed 510 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN and CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YARROW Shipbuilders, GEC's naval shipyard in Glasgow, is to shed 510 jobs
because of a gap in its order book. The jobs are in ship outfitting, one of
the final stages in shipbuilding.
Yarrow is finishing two ships now and has orders for a further five
frigates, and outfitters for these ships will not be needed for 12 to 18
months. The company said yesterday that it will then employ the number of
staff losing jobs now.
Yarrow, which employs 2,750 people, cut 645 jobs last December, mainly in
fabrication, as it finished work on the Type 23 frigates Iron Duke and
Monmouth. The fresh wave of redundancies comes in spite of orders for five
frigates earlier this year. In January the shipyard won a Pounds 400m order
for three more Type 23 frigates for the Royal Navy. Yarrow had hoped for
earlier orders, but the government procurement process was slowed by the
Options For Change defence spending document.
Yarrow was also awarded a Pounds 322m contract in January for two frigates
for the Malaysian government. That was the first overseas warship order for
Yarrow since it was sold by the government in 1985.
Work has started on the three Navy frigates and design work is under way on
the Malaysian order. Both contracts will maintain work at the yard until
1997. Yarrow said they 'were too late to maintain continuity of employment'.
Volunteers will be sought, but there are likely to be compulsorily
redundancies. The jobs will be cut by the end of the year.
Mr John Carty, Clyde district secretary of the AEEU engineering and
electricians' union, said he was 'extremely disappointed'. He would meet
management next week to look for ways to cushion the blow.
Mr Frank Dobson, shadow employment secretary, said the announcement was
another nail in Britain's industrial coffin. 'If we throw people in
manufacturing jobs out of work we will only end up importing what they used
to make, which is a disaster for everyone,' he said.
The UK's biggest offshore module yard yesterday warned that it may have to
shed 1,500 jobs next spring unless it wins orders it is pursuing against
intense competition, Chris Tighe writes.
The warning from AMEC Offshore, which operates extensive facilities on the
Tyne and employs 3,500 people, underlines the serious job-loss implications
of the downturn in the offshore industry.
In the past 10 days nearly 400 jobs have been lost in north-east England's
offshore sector. Redpath Offshore on Teesside, part of the Trafalgar House
group cut 200 jobs while 196 went at AMEC Offshore, including the loss of 76
which will take effect today.
AMEC Offshore completed two large contracts this summer and work on the
current order book will end next spring.
Yesterday the company said the 1,500 job losses would affect both direct
employees and subcontractors taken on in the past year. It added that the
figure was a 'worst-case scenario' - it hopes its tenders for projects in
Norway and the UK sectors of the North Sea will win more orders.
ELECTRICIANS employed by Swan Hunter, the Tyneside shipbuilder, yesterday
staged a 24-hour unofficial strike to protest at the provision of training
in electrical work for boilermakers on the company's payroll, Chris Tighe
writes.
The action by 550 electricians was condemned by senior union officials. It
highlights the problems faced by UK shipyards in maintaining a balanced
range of workforce skills while fighting to replenish dwindling order books.
Swan Hunter has some orders up to the end of 1994, but its workload now
consists almost entirely of outfitting. It needs to retain men in the
front-end steel trades in order to bid successfully for new orders.
The company, which last Friday announced 1,425 job losses among employees
and contract workers, reducing its workforce to 2,200, has identified 100
boilermakers whom it plans to train to work in other trade areas. The first
batch of 11 are due to start on-the-job electrical training today.
The electricians held a meeting yesterday morning and failed to return to
work.
The company said yesterday that training for multi-skilled working was
within the provisions of its versatility agreement. Mr John Cunningham,
chairman of the Confederation of Shipbuilding and Engineering Unions at
Swans, said the action by the electricians had breached that agreement. 'We
have agreements with the company; some people have misunderstood them,' he
said.
Mr Cunningham said a meeting between union leaders and management yesterday
afternoon had produced a solution to be put to shop stewards today. The
versatility agreement would be honoured and work would continue normally, he
pledged.
</TEXT>
