<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / Abu Dhabi briefed on BCCI investigation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS, ROBERT PESTON and ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH officials are confident that criticism of Abu Dhabi's role in the
Bank of Credit and Commerce International affair by the inquiry headed by
Lord Justice Bingham will not be so severe as to risk a row between the two
governments.
Officials say criticism of Abu Dhabi's role in the affair is far less
extensive than that levelled at other institutions, especially the Bank of
England.
Extracts from Lord Justice Bingham's final conclusions relating to Abu Dhabi
were circulated among Foreign Office officials early last week after being
delivered to the Treasury and the Bank of England. This followed months of
activity by UK diplomats aimed at limiting the damage the BCCI affair might
do to relations between the UK and Abu Dhabi, the majority shareholder in
BCCI. Last year the United Arab Emirates, which includes Abu Dhabi, was the
UK's second largest trading partner in the Middle East after Saudi Arabia.
A draft of the Bingham report criticises Abu Dhabi for delaying giving the
Bank of England information on the scale of the fraud at BCCI. It highlights
as a serious omission a nine-month delay in communicating details of the
losses and fraud - including the theft of Dollars 2.2bn of Abu Dhabi's
funds.
Abu Dhabi and its advisers are understood to reject what they see as a slur
on the emirate's reputation, but Abu Dhabi government representatives have
reassured British officials that the emirate is prepared to continue to keep
bilateral relations separate from the issue of BCCI.
It is understood that Abu Dhabi is considering a study prepared by the
Ministry of Defence on how UK military personnel and defence equipment could
be used in the reorganisation and modernisation of armed forces in the UAE,
which Britain considers an important ally against Iraq.
A federal judge in Washington has been asked to order Abu Dhabi to hand over
shares of First American Bankshares, the US bank illegally controlled by
BCCI, Alan Friedman in New York writes.
The move was instigated by lawyers for Mr Harry Albright, the independent
trustee for First American appointed last June after the Federal Reserve
Board ordered that the bank be sold. Mr Albright said the action followed
long negotiations that failed to persuade Abu Dhabi to hand over the shares.
Mr Sandy Martin, a partner at the Washington law firm of Patton, Boggs and
Blow, representing Abu Dhabi, said the shares had been registered in Mr
Albright's name. However, some of the shares are held by Abu Dhabi as
security on a Dollars 9.5m loan.
'We believe that unless we are told otherwise by a court it is our
obligation to retain possession of the certificates,' Mr Martin said.
</TEXT>
