<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / US dismisses China's protest on F-16 sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN, YVONNE PRESTON and WILLIAM KEELING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, BEIJING,, JAKARTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE WHITE House yesterday rejected the strongest protest heard from China in
a long time over the decision by President George Bush to permit the sale of
US warplanes to Taiwan.
China accused Washington of being untrustworthy and of violating the Sino-US
joint communique of August 1982, expressing itself 'shocked and outraged'.
China threatened to withdraw from arms control talks between the five
permanent members of the United Nations Security Council if the decision to
supply Taiwan with 150 F-16 fighters was not reversed.
However, Mr Marlin Fitzwater, the White House spokesman, immediately
dismissed the Chinese objections. 'The president made his decision based on
the stability of the region,' he said. US officials noted that China had
recently acquired enough modern Russian-built fighters to throw Taiwan's air
defence capabilities 'out of kilter'. The Chinese protest warned of 'a major
retrogression' in Sino-US relations and said this would have a negative
impact on bilateral co-operation in the UN and other international
organisations.
Qian Qichen, the Chinese foreign minister, said 'the US government should be
held accountable for any serious consequences'. At a press conference in
Jakarta, where he is leading a delegation to the Non-Aligned summit, he
added: 'On the one hand, the US government is arguing for arms control, but
on the other hand it is selling such sophisticated fighters.'
Mr J Stapleton Roy, the US ambassador to China, was summoned to the Foreign
Ministry in Beijing yesterday to be told by Liu Huaqiu, vice-foreign
minister, that the decision was a gross interference in China's internal
affairs and 'undermines the great cause of China's peaceful reunification'.
The 1982 communique, one of three agreements forming the basis of Sino-US
relations, expresses US intent to 'reduce gradually sale of arms to Taiwan,
leading over a period of time to a final resolution'. Mr Bush helped
negotiate the understanding with China a decade ago.
Proponents of the F-16 sale argue that the US has the right to provide
Taiwan with the arms that it needs for its defence.
The sale of US warplanes to Taiwan was blocked during the cold war.
Washington needed China's help as a counterweight to the military strength
of the old Soviet Union. The role of China in this formerly critical balance
has vanished.
China's rebuke to the US is likely to add to its unpopularity in Congress
where its human rights record is under criticism and its most favoured
nation trade status under debate.
Editorial Comment, Page 18
</TEXT>
