<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / Mitterrand warns on Maastricht rejection
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Francois Mitterrand last night raised the French referendum
campaign on Maastricht to a new pitch, warning in a three-hour television
debate that rejection of the treaty would be a 'serious setback' for France
and Europe.
Mr Mitterrand, whose approval rating has been in steady decline, refused to
make any link between the outcome of the September 20 vote and his own
political future.
In his first TV debate for four years, Mr Mitterrand sought to explain and
defend the treaty on political and economic union. As well as fending off
spirited and often hostile questioning from selected private citizens, he
crossed swords in a surprisingly courteous duel with Mr Philippe Seguin,
Gaullist standard bearer of the No campaign.
With opinion polls indicating a close result, the impact of the debate on
the referendum is hard to predict, given that neither Mr Mitterrand nor his
antagonist made any serious blunder.
The see-saw nature of the referendum campaign was highlighted by publication
of a poll conducted earlier this week for Societe Generale, the French bank,
showing 52 per cent of the electorate planned to vote No. This poll
contradicted five others published this week, all indicating a narrow Yes
majority. The TV marathon was marked by an intervention from German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl, who told French viewers that fears of losing their
identity in the EC were misplaced. He saw no reason for any French
'inferiority complex'.
Mr Mitterrand said the Germans were 'making a big sacrifice' in agreeing to
monetary union. 'Their pride is the D-Mark,' he said.
In his case for a No vote, Mr Seguin strongly criticised Mr Mitterrand for
committing France to a single monetary policy over which it would have
little control and for pushing France towards the goal of a federal Europe.
Mr Seguin stressed that Britain had won the right to opt out of monetary
union, but France had not.
Mr Mitterrand claimed Maastricht was necessary for the European Community to
protect itself. While barriers were coming down between EC states, the
Community still lacked common policies to assure its internal and external
security.
He acknowledged that a referendum defeat would pose severe problems for him.
But 'worn' though he and his unpopular Socialist government were, he denied
he was such a liability that he should step down to win approval for
Maastricht.
Mr Seguin called for renegotiation of Maastricht to introduce more democracy
into EC decision-making, a bigger say for national parliaments, a new common
currency in parallel to national currencies, and a greater opening to east
Europe.
A Yes vote in the French referendum is a clear favourite with the
bookmakers. Ladbrokes is quoting 1-2 (bet Pounds 2 to win Pounds 1) for a
majority in favour, with a No vote offered at 11-8.
The French Referendum, Page 3
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
