<HEADLINE>
FT  04 SEP 92 / Thatcher attacks Major's stance on EC union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR last night faced fresh criticism from Lady Thatcher over
Britain's economy and its approach to Europe as he prepared to underline his
personal commitment to the Maastricht treaty on European union.
In another thinly veiled attack on her successor, the former prime minister
said Mr Major's determination to hold sterling's value against the D-Mark in
the European exchange rate mechanism was prolonging the British recession.
In a phrase recalling her battles over exchange rate policy with her former
chancellor Mr Nigel Lawson (now Lord Lawson), she added: 'If by artificially
controlling the exchange rates between countries you try to buck the market,
you will soon find the market bucks you - and hard.'
Her remarks - delivered in a speech in South Korea - came as the Foreign
Office signalled that Mr Major would reaffirm his strong support for
Maastricht in an important speech on Monday when he opens the flagship
conference of Britain's EC presidency.
Mr Tristan Garel-Jones, the Foreign Office minister responsible for Europe,
said Mr Major remained convinced that Maastricht was 'good for Britain and
good for Europe'.
Mr Major plans to devote most of his speech to setting out his vision of a
wider, liberal and outward-looking Europe, but Mr Garel-Jones said the prime
minister would 'undoubtedly re-emphasise' his firm commitment to Maastricht.
Speaking at the launch of the conference, Mr Garel-Jones said the UK
expected the French electorate to vote Yes in the September 20 referendum.
'I do not anticipate the collapse of the Maastricht treaty. I do not
anticipate anything but a Yes vote.'
But he acknowledged also that in its role as EC president, the UK was
drawing up contingency plans in the event of the treaty's rejection by
France.
Among the starting points were the commitment to maintain sterling within
the ERM, and an assumption that the intergovernmental co-operation on
foreign and defence policies enshrined in Maastricht would proceed without a
formal treaty.
Whitehall officials said the plans included an emergency meeting of EC
foreign ministers in New York on the day after the referendum. The
ministers, who will be attending the United Nations general assembly, could
then decide to call for an emergency summit of EC leaders.
Lady Thatcher's intervention provided a further reminder to Mr Major that,
whatever the French result, his party's Euro-sceptics plan a concentrated
campaign to prevent ratification of the treaty by the British parliament.
In a speech which also included a number of transparent sideswipes against
rising public spending and borrowing by Mr Major's government, Lady Thatcher
drew parallels with the disintegration of the former Yugoslavia and warned
that attempts to create artificial federations fuelled nationalism and
risked conflict.
</TEXT>
