<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 92 / Classic blast for Radio 3
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
CLASSIC FM, Britain's first national commercial radio station, yesterday
criticised BBC Radio 3 for moving towards its position in the marketplace.
Mr John Spearman, chief executive of the new station, to be launched on
Monday, said the recent format changes at Radio 3 seemed to be taking it
towards the position it thought Classic FM would occupy.
Mr Spearman, who said he was an avid Radio 3 listener, said: 'This reduces
consumer choice rather than expanding it. I am sorry about that.'
There was plenty of room for both Radio 3 and Classic FM in the market, he
said.
The new station, which will broadcast on a range of frequencies from 100-102
FM in different parts of the company, will open at 6am on Monday with
Handel's God Save The King.
The first advertisement - advertising sales have already exceeded Pounds
1.3m in just over two months - will be for Barclays Bank.
Classic FM, which will concentrate on melodic classical music, hopes to
attract a weekly audience of 2.8m - 70 per cent of them from the ABC1 social
groups.
</TEXT>
