FT  03 SEP 92 / Rafsanjani attacks US at Non-Aligned Summit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM KEELING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JAKARTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Iran's President Ali Akbar Rafsanjani acknowledges applause after a speech
at the Non-Aligned Movement summit in Jakarta yesterday in which he attacked
the US's role in the Middle East. Mr Rafsanjani said that supporters of
Israel 'have gained an unprecedented and shameless presence in the region on
the pretext of protecting Kuwait' and condemned 'the continuous
interferences' by the US in the region, writes William Keeling in Jakarta.
Dr Mahathir Mohamad, the Malaysian prime minister, said he was perplexed by
the 'no-fly' zone in southern Iraq, set up by Washington to protect the Shia
community from attack by Baghdad. 'Maybe there are a lot of Shias in
America,' he quipped.
