<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 92 / Move to oust Tajik leader
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUSHANBE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TAJIKISTAN'S cabinet and parliamentary presidium yesterday passed a vote of
no-confidence in President Rakhmon Nabiyev, the country's hard-line
communist leader, AP reports Dushanbe.
Tajik radio and television, which reported the vote, said government and
parliament leaders called a parliamentary session tomorrow to decide Mr
Nabiyev's fate.
Mr Nabiyev was believed to be in a garrison of the former Soviet army in
Dushanbe and he reportedly met one representative of the cabinet there
yesterday morning.
His status as a popularly elected president leaves the legal consequences of
the no-confidence vote in doubt.
Meanwhile, anti-government protesters who had been holding 35 officials
hostage in the presidential palace released all their captives late
yesterday.
</TEXT>
