FT  03 SEP 92 / International Company News: Premium brands lift Seagram
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SEAGRAM, one of the top four drinks groups, says its policy of concentrating
on higher-margin premium brands is being reflected in higher profits.
For the second quarter ended July 31 sales of spirits, wines and other
beverages gained 2 per cent to USDollars 1.41bn, more than making up for the
sale of several North American spirits brands in 1991.
Operating income was Dollars 160m, against Dollars 120m. After including
Dollars 72m in dividends from its 25 per cent interest in EI du Pont de
Nemours (Dollars 69m a year earlier), and Dollars 33m equity in unremitted
du Pont earnings, compared with Dollars 61m, Seagram's final net profit was
Dollars 152m, or 41 cents a share, against Dollars 149m, or 23 cents, a year
earlier.
First-half final net profit was Dollars 319m, or 85 cents, down from Dollars
337m, or 89 cents, a year earlier, because of lower equity in du Pont's
earnings. Sales were Dollars 2.65bn, against Dollars 2.78bn.
In June, Seagram increased its 49 per cent interest in a Venezuelan
distiller and a Venezuelan distributor to 100 per cent. This was in line
with its policy of developing premium brands worldwide.
Metall Mining, a fast-growing Canadian resource holding company controlled
by Germany's Metallgesellschaft, earned CDollars 3.87m (USDollars 3.25m), or
8 cents a share, in the first half, against a loss of CDollars 2.5m, or 6
cents, a year earlier, on revenues of CDollars 106m against CDollars 84.4m.
