FT  03 SEP 92 / International Company News: Canadian bank hit by O&amp;Y loans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ROYAL BANK of Canada, the country's biggest financial institution, suffered
a 57 per cent plunge in third-quarter income largely due to further
write-downs on its loans to ailing property developer Olympia &amp; York.
RBC has classified its entire CDollars 766m (USDollars 643.6m) exposure to
O&amp;Y as non-performing. The company said yesterday a significant, but not the
entire, amount would be written off as a charge against income.
More than a third of RBC's exposure is in the form of participation in a
jumbo loan secured by O&amp;Y's shares in Abitibi-Price, newsprint maker, and
Gulf Canada Resources, energy producer.
The O&amp;Y losses have been partly instrumental in Royal more than doubling its
estimate of specific loan losses for fiscal 1992 to CDollars 1.45bn, from
CDollars 705m last year.
The company said the rest of the increase was due mainly to difficulties at
Central Capital, a troubled Canadian financial institution, and to other
real estate borrowers in the Toronto area.
Recoveries of earlier provisions for Third World loans would however, reduce
the losses charged against income to CDollars 1.15bn for 1992, versus
CDollars 605m last year.
Net earnings slid to CDollars 112.4m, or 26 cents a share, in the three
months to July 31, from CDollars 261.3m, or 77 cents, a year earlier.
Loan-loss provisions for the quarter soared to CDollars 390m from CDollars
155m, but were partly offset by wider domestic interest rate margins and by
a strong contribution from RBC Dominion Securities, the bank's securities
dealer subsidiary. Dominion Securities earned almost CDollars 25m in the
third quarter.
The return on equity tumbled to 5 per cent from 16.1 per cent, and return on
assets was down to 0.33 per cent from 0.80 per cent. Total assets stood at
CDollars 139.5bn on July 31, up from CDollars 130.2bn a year earlier.
Total non-performing loans, excluding Third World debt, have jumped in the
past year to CDollars 2.85bn from CDollars 1.79bn.
In spite of its loan problems, RBC maintains a strong capital position. Its
ratio of total capital to assets was 9.5 per cent on July 31, or 10.3 per
cent if measured by US regulatory definitions.
