<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 92 / Cut power bill 'nuclear levy', regulator urges: Nuclear
Electric attacks untimely interference
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROFESSOR Stephen Littlechild, the electricity industry regulator, yesterday
added his voice to calls for a reduction in the 11 per cent 'nuclear levy'
on electricity bills, provoking a clash with Nuclear Electric, the
state-owned generator.
He proposed a 'faster and more certain reduction' of the nuclear levy,
imposed after privatisation of non-nuclear generators in 1990 to subsidise
the higher costs of nuclear electricity.
Prof Littlechild, director general of electricity supply, was addressing the
Energy Intensive Users Group; one of the groups representing large
electricity consumers which have repeatedly warned that the competitiveness
of UK industry may be harmed unless prices are lowered.
The call came only a day after PowerGen, the privatised generator, said it
had been discussing a reduction in the levy with large energy users and the
Department of Trade and Industry for several months. Rival generator
National Power said yesterday it also supported this strategy.
The DTI said Prof Littlechild was free to express his views, but reiterated
that in discussions with large users on electricity prices it had made clear
there could be 'no question of public subsidies'.
Mr Robert Hawley, Nuclear Electric's chief executive, wrote to Prof
Littlechild on Tuesday but failed to dissuade him from publishing his
proposals. In a strongly worded protest, Mr Hawley called the move
'unjustifiable and untimely interference'.
Prof Littlechild proposed changing regulations to allow the rate of the levy
to be fixed in advance, enabling customers to plan more effectively. At
present it is revised yearly on the basis of projected electricity demand to
ensure it raises a set amount. He also suggested that the rate should
steadily decrease, to give Nuclear Electric a 'sharper incentive to improve
efficiency'.
'In a fully competitive market, customers would not have to pay the higher
costs of nuclear electricity,' Prof Littlechild said. 'A reduction in the
levy would, therefore, be a most practical and defensible way of responding
to concerns from larger users.'
Mr Hawley said the proposal was unacceptable as it did not recognise that
any levy shortfall would have to be made up out of public expenditure.
He added that Nuclear Electric had a sharp incentive to cut costs by its
public commitment to making an operating profit before the levy by 1995. He
called Prof Littlechild's statement on competition and the costs of nuclear
electricity 'fanciful'.
Mr Andrew Bainbridge, director of the Major Energy Users Council, said he
would prefer any cut in electricity prices to be aimed specifically at
industry.
'Although we sympathise with anyone who is trying to make ends meet in a
recession, we do feel the large user needs special treatment at a time when
industry is sinking fast,' he said.
Hidden tax on power, Page 8
Letter, Page 19
</TEXT>
