<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 92 / Insurance solvency formula 'absurd'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INSURANCE industry regulators were criticised yesterday over alleged
inadequacies in the way they assess the solvency of general insurance
companies.
Mr Andrew Paddick, director-general of the Institute of Insurance Brokers,
said the formula used by the Department of Trade and Industry to assess
solvency - net assets as a percentage of non-life premium income - was
'totally absurd'.
The institute, a trade association, was particularly concerned in view of
the deteriorating financial health of many UK insurers.
Mr Paddick explained that increased competition in the industry had rendered
the solvency ratio an increasingly inadequate guide to the ability of
insurance companies to meet claims.
Insurers could trigger falls in their solvency if they increased premiums
while, ironically, cutting premiums to uneconomic levels would be rewarded
with an increase in the solvency margin.
'Years ago, when tariffs kept rates stable and risks were properly
evaluated, it may have made some sense to use such a formula,' he said.
One small insurance company, which became insolvent earlier this year, had a
solvency margin of 71.4 per cent at the end of 1990. Mr Paddick said that
was more than four times the legal minimum.
He said brokers and other insurance buyers needed more detailed information
to assess the viability of companies with which they placed business.
Mr Denzil Curgenven, of Quest Insurance Research, a market research
organisation, said other factors were as important a guide to a company's
economic well-being as the solvency ratio.
These included the strength of the company's financial base, the details of
its reinsurance arrangements, the type of insurance it underwrote and the
size of its management expenses.
A new research service, published by the institute and Quest, provides
analysis on 70 UK insurance companies.
Mr Curgenven said: 'You can't judge a company on one factor, certainly not
in today's market. The fortunes of UK insurers have changed with bewildering
speed.'
Lancashire police yesterday made 16 arrests in connection with an alleged
fraud at the Preston offices of General Accident, the country's third
largest insurer.
The arrests were made after raids on 13 homes in north-west England. General
Accident confirmed that a member of its staff was among those arrested.
Police said that the alleged fraud involved false claims worth several
hundred thousands of pounds on 'third party' insurance policies which had
been made over a number of years.
</TEXT>
