<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 92 / Mixed marks for home work: Is teleworking is the future, or
merely the fantasy of futurists?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE announcement that managers and professional staff at British
Telecommunications are to be allowed to apply to work from home must have
left many commuters wondering this week how they managed to miss the
revolution that makes 'teleworking' so apparently straightforward.
BT says the agreement it has reached with the managers' union, the Society
of Telecom Executives, could mean up to 8,000 employees becoming eligible
for the homeworking scheme. The company would continue to provide the same
pay and benefits to those who chose to work from home, as well as meeting
extra heating and telephone costs.
From the employee's point of view working from home brings obvious benefits,
such as extra flexibility in hours and the elimination of travelling time.
For the employer there is the prospect of cutting office overheads and
seeing productivity increase.
The teleworking revolution has clearly yet to happen. A handful of
companies, particularly those in the new technology field such as CPS, the
ICL software subsidiary, have a largely home-based workforce. Others have
introduced teleworking on an ad hoc basis to retain particular employees, or
are experimenting with small groups of workers. British Airways has just
finished a six-month trial with a dozen employees in its information
management department.
The Department of Employment says there are no authoritative figures for
teleworking. The first indication of how widespread it is will be available
in about three months.
The latest estimates, now more than 10 years old, showed between 1.6 per
cent and 2.6 per cent of the working population work from home. Those
figures cover every home worker, from the piece-worker who hand-finishes
garments to the management consultant.
If any company is able to operate large-scale teleworking it ought to be BT,
with its access to the latest technology. It is also in BT's interests to
lead by example and stimulate sales of the telecommunications hardware and
services that make teleworking possible. So it is surprising that fewer than
50 managers or professionals out of BT's workforce of more than 200,000 work
principally from home.
There has been a steady stream of BT publications and surveys extolling the
virtues of teleworking. The latest, The Economics of Teleworking, concluded
that productivity per worker increased by about 45 per cent when the switch
was made to working at home. It also argued national savings could be made
through lower commuting bills, fewer road accidents and less pollution.
The question is whether the teleworking revolution will ever take place  -
or remain a fantasy of futurists.
Mr Andrew Wilson, a researcher for Sussex University's Institute of Manpower
Studies, considers it is 'unlikely that there will be a wholesale
substitution of the workplace from the office to the home'.
In a report called Teleworking - Flexibility for a Few, he envisages a
future in which employees divide their time between the two locations. He
says: 'In this way, the distinction between 'home worker' and 'office
worker' will become less relevant as more and more people become accustomed
to carrying out part of their work outside the main office.'
Mr Wilson identifies a number of potential constraints on the wholesale
development of teleworking, among them the unwillingness of organisations to
alter their management techniques radically.
He points out that in the traditional office 'most managers tend to
supervise their staff by direct observation and monitoring'.
He adds: 'Managers are able to set tasks, prescribe objectives, monitor
feedback and assess performance with an immediacy that is not possible with
remote workers.'
Teleworking, on the other hand, demands more formalised management
procedures and may require an increase in the management time devoted to
each employee. The study quotes research into one of the longest-standing
teleworking operations, at FI Group, a software developer. This research
apparently revealed that each manager at the company supervised fewer than
half the number of staff managed by counterparts in other British software
companies.
The lack of visibility also has an effect on employees. The dangers of
individuals becoming lonely, and feeling deprived of the social advantages
of working with other people, are easy to imagine.
According to the Henley Centre for Forecasting only about half of employees
would want to work from home, even if their jobs allowed for it.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
