<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 92 / Names offered risk-spread plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE OF the largest agencies at Lloyd's of London is to introduce a scheme
allowing Names, the individuals whose assets support underwriting at the
insurance market, to spread their underwriting risks more widely.
The scheme, which is being introduced by Sedgwick Lloyd's Underwriting
Agents, is similar to the members' agency pooling arrangements or MAPAs, the
introduction of which was recommended by the Rowland task force earlier this
year.
Like an MAPA, the Sedgwick Standard Programme will allow Names to support a
larger number of syndicates, reducing their exposure to syndicates that
perform particularly badly.
Mr Julian Crispin, the chairman of the agency, said the Sedgwick scheme,
which fits within the current regulatory framework at Lloyd's, 'should help
Names avoid peaks and troughs in their underwriting'. It was particularly
suitable for Names wanting to take a 'defensive attitude to their
underwriting'.
Demand from Names for a way to spread risks has increased after recent
losses have been concentrated among a small minority of Names, for example
in the catastrophe reinsurance market.
The authorities at Lloyd's have agreed to introduce MAPAs but are still
discussing the fiscal and regulatory implications with regulators.
Mr Crispin said it could take between two and three years to introduce MAPAs
 -the Rowland task force recommended that they be in place for the 1993
underwriting year.
Mr Crispin said as many as 600 Names whose affairs the agency currently
managed had expressed interest, and 200 Names had already agreed to
underwrite through the scheme in 1993.
On average Names underwriting at Lloyd's through conventional methods would
participate on between 10 and 15 syndicates. Those participating through the
programme will have a share in the 41 syndicates with which Sedgwick places
most of its business.
Each unit of the Sedgwick Standard Programme will comprise 41 syndicates
with a total capacity of Pounds 50,000. most Names would normally subscribe
for more than one unit. Other agencies could make similar initiatives as the
market seeks to persuade the 22,300 Names underwriting in 1992 to continue
their membership of Lloyd's.
Lloyd's said last week that 686 Names had resigned so far this year. The
number of open years at Lloyd's has nearly doubled in the last 12 months.
</TEXT>
