<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 92 / School heads reject performance pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HEAD TEACHERS oppose government plans to introduce performance-related pay
for teachers, the National Association of Head Teachers said yesterday .
It published a survey by the independent Institute of Manpower Studies based
on 3,300 responses from a sample of 5,081 heads in England and Wales. The
survey indicated that heads were almost universally sceptical about
performance pay.
But the survey also found that heads felt the current pay system did not
give them enough scope to reward teachers. While just under half the
teachers in the schools of heads surveyed received an incentive allowance,
80 per cent of the awards were for extra responsibility. Only 3 per cent
were awarded for classroom performance and little use was made of other
flexibilities in the pay system.
The heads generally welcomed greater control over their school budgets but
there was considerable concern over additional workload and stress.
Staying a Head, Institute of Manpower Studies, Mantell Building, University
of Sussex, Falmer, Brighton BN1 9RF. Pounds 10 plus Pounds 1.75 p&amp;p.
</TEXT>
