<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 92 / Bank silent on action against loans row man
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN ASIAN businessman whose 'interest-free loan' dealings are being
investigated by police was the subject two years ago of a Bank of England
injunction restraining him from taking deposits.
Yesterday the Bank could not say whether Mr Mohammed Ramzan's subsequent
business activities had been monitored or why the injunction had been
sought.
An official said: 'We are constrained in talking about our activities in
supervision in relation to any specific individual or institution.' She
confirmed that Mr Ramzan's company Moslem World Finance is not, and never
has been, an authorised institution under the Banking Act.
Moslems in many parts of England fear they have lost substantial sums
invested in the Bradford-based company, whose interest-free loans seemed to
satisfy the Koran's ban on interest-bearing dealings.
Mr Ramzan closed his Bradford office and disappeared about a month ago,
leaving behind many clients who claim he owes them substantial sums of
money.
Moslem World Finance appeared to offer Moslems a solution to their dilemma
of trying to reconcile the practices of western financial institutions with
the Koran.
The company promised that investors depositing an interest-free lump sum for
one year would then receive their money back, plus an interest-free loan of
three times that amount, which could be used to pay off their mortgages.
Some clients remortgaged their homes to raise the lump sum; several now face
repossession. It is unclear how many people invested in the scheme.
Mr Ramzan consented to the terms of the Bank's injunction obtained in the
High Court in August 1990.
West Yorkshire CID have sent an initial report to the Fraud Squad. Police
sources say inquiries are at an early stage but that the total sum involved
is likely to be more than Pounds 1m. Mr Liaqat Hussain, president of
Bradford's Council for Mosques, said he feared the amount invested could be
much higher.
Mr David Musa Pidcock, leader of the Islamic Party of Britain, and of a
committee formed by 34 investors who deposited between Pounds 5,500 and
Pounds 31,000 each, confirmed that Mr Ramzan had received lump sum deposits
in 1991 and this year.
The Central Register of the Securities and Investments Board said yesterday
that MWF's activities came to its notice in 1990. It decided it did not need
SIB registration as it did not appear to be an investment business. SIB
referred the case to the Bank of England, which regulates deposit-taking
business.
The telephone at MWF's office rang unanswered yesterday. Earlier this week
Mr Ramzan rang the Telegraph and Argus, Bradford's evening newspaper, saying
he was in fear of his life, but he declined to be interviewed.
</TEXT>
