<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 92 / Analyst opts for room with a view
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE woodland of the Scottish borders is the vista that greets City
investment analyst Tessa Tennant at her desk.
It is worlds away from London's Knightsbridge where, until January last
year, Ms Tennant, 33, was based as head of environmental research at Jupiter
Tyndall Merlin (JTM), the investment management arm of Jupiter Tyndall, the
fund management group.
Today she does the same job but works three out of every four weeks from her
home near Peebles. In her office, once the house library, antique furnishing
rubs shoulders with modern equipment.
Ms Tennant is a telecommuter. She said the trial arrangement, which ends
this month, had benefited both herself and her employer. This year she was
made a director.
Ms Tennant has worked for JTM for more than four years. About three years
ago she began managing Glen, the large estate and conference centre which is
her home. She also needed to spend more time with her nine-year-old son,
Euan.
Ms Tennant said: 'Much of the JTM work I do is research and involves a lot
of writing and reading. It is a job that can be done anywhere provided you
have a personal computer, fax and telephone.
'At the office you are too available - people are always popping in for ad
hoc meetings or chats. Many analysts find it quite difficult to sit down and
do research.'
Ms Tennant's working day starts when she takes her son to school. She then
knuckles down to work either for JTM or the conference centre.
The day ends in the late afternoon. She does not usually need to work until
five. 'I can easily return to my desk late in the evening.'
Mr Michael Heathcoat Amory, managing director of JTM, said: 'The arrangement
has worked perfectly satisfactorily.' He stressed, however, the importance
of Ms Tennant's monthly visits to London because of the need for personal
contact.
Ms Tennant said that the support of colleagues had been important to the
experiment's success. 'I have a very close working relationship with the
team in London. I have discovered that it is possible to function as a team
even if you are not all in the same room. It is a question of not letting
team-mates down.'
</TEXT>
