FT  03 SEP 92 / Checkland denies he will quit BBC early
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR MICHAEL CHECKLAND, director-general of the BBC, insisted yesterday that
he would continue in his job until the end of his contract, contrary to
recent reports, Raymond Snoddy writes.
Sunday newspapers had suggested that Sir Michael would go early to clear the
way for Mr John Birt, director-general designate, and that Radio 2 and Radio
5 faced closure.
Sir Michael said yesterday that he would remain director- general until his
contract ended next February, adding that there was no plan to scrap any BBC
radio channel.
He said the BBC would set out a clear vision of its future shortly after the
government published a planned green paper in the autumn.
Sir Michael said there would be a restatement of the role of BBC governors
and management, implying that the governors would stick to strategy and
appointing top executives.
The reports on Sunday followed a public row between Mr Michael Grade, chief
executive of Channel 4, and Mr Marmaduke Hussey, BBC chairman. Mr Grade
attacked BBC management and governors at the Edinburgh Television Festival
last week for a 'pseudo-Leninist style of management'.
Mr Hussey responded by describing Mr Grade as 'a Bourbon in red braces'.
