<HEADLINE>
FT  03 SEP 92 / 'Yes' campaign gaining ground, polls indicate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN and ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TWO opinion polls yesterday forecast that France would narrowly approve the
Maastricht treaty on European union at a referendum this month, as European
leaders rallied to support President Francois Mitterrand in his campaign for
a 'Yes' vote.
Mr Mitterrand, who will tonight take part in his first television debate in
four years, has been under growing pressure since opinion polls began to
show a majority against the treaty a week ago.
Other European leaders, with their own agendas at stake, have begun adding
their weight to the 'Yes' campaign. Spanish prime minister Felipe Gonzalez
told a rally in Strasbourg last night that Europe must overcome the
nationalist drive that unleashed two world wars. German chancellor Helmut
Kohl is to make a satellite appearance tonight on French television.
The debate between the Socialist president and Mr Philippe Seguin, the most
prominent neo-Gaullist opponent of the treaty, will set the tone in the
final stage of the referendum campaign, which is balanced on a knife-edge
margin between the 'Yes' and 'No' camps.
Two polls published yesterday showed a shift in sentiment indicating a small
majority for 'Yes'. The BVA/Paris Match poll suggested that 51 per cent of
the electorate would support ratification. The same poll last week indicated
that exactly the same proportion would vote 'No'. An IPSOS/Le Point poll
suggested a 53 per cent majority in favour, against last week's poll which
suggested the 'Yes' faction would lose with just 48 per cent.
Yesterday's polls support the general trend of this week's surveys, which
show growing support for the treaty, although still by a slim margin.
Tonight's debate will offer a chance for Mr Mitterrand to salvage his
political credibility at a time when his future has been called into
question. The anti-Maastricht camp has been trying to turn the referendum
into a vote of no confidence in him and the Socialist government.
The BVA/Paris Match poll yesterday showed that the president's approval
rating has fallen from 35 per cent to 33 per cent in the past month. This
means Mr Mitterrand is uncomfortably close to his all-time popularity poll
low of 31 per cent on the eve of this spring's regional elections.
Mr Pierre Beregovoy, the Socialist prime minister whose appointment after
the regional elections briefly boosted the president's poll standing, has
seen his approval rating fall from 41 per cent to 35 per cent since July.
The constitutional court yesterday rejected an appeal by conservative
opponents of the treaty, who had been trying to block ratification on
constitutional grounds.
The French stock market, which was depressed last week by the threat of a
negative referendum result, recovered momentum yesterday. The CAC 40 Index
ended the day 1.57 per cent higher at 1,700,50.
