<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 92 / International Company News: O&amp;Y may seek US bankruptcy
protection
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OLYMPIA &amp; YORK, the troubled Canadian property developer, has concluded it
may have to seek protection from creditors under US bankruptcy law unless it
can satisfy demands from a loan syndicate led by JP Morgan.
Mr Paul Reichmann, O&amp;Y's chief strategist, and Mr Gerald Greenwald,
president, were in New York yesterday for meetings aimed at avoiding a US
bankruptcy filing. An O&amp;Y official said the company 'may be left with no
option but to file under Chapter 11'. The official said: 'If we can't find
an accommodation with Morgan then we will have to seek protection in the
US.'
The latest conflict between O&amp;Y and JP Morgan comes four months after a
Morgan-led loan syndicate said it would foreclose on part of a Dollars 160m
loan. This announcement was followed by postponements of the foreclosure
auction and by the termination of Morgan's other role as a financial adviser
to O&amp;Y.
Three weeks ago the Morgan-led loan syndicate asked O&amp;Y to place the cash
flow generated by six healthy US buildings into a bank account that would
have Morgan as a trustee. Morgan's aim was to ensure O&amp;Y would have
sufficient funds for interest payments on the Dollars 160m loan, as well as
the cost of maintenance and tax payments on its US buildings.
O&amp;Y countered by asking Morgan to withdraw its request for the trusteeship
accounts, although the Canadian-based group did satisfy the Morgan syndicate
that sufficient funds would be set aside.
Morgan has now told O&amp;Y it would drop other requests if the developer agreed
to set up separate bank accounts to contain US cash flow. Morgan set a
deadline of September 3 for O&amp;Y to accept the compromise proposal, but one
banker said the Morgan-led group would not necessarily act to seize assets
if O&amp;Y did not comply with the deadline.
</TEXT>
