<TEXT>
GENERAL MOTORS is to invest more than Dollars 20m in a new plant in
Argentina, 13 years after it withdrew from the country.
It will invest about Dollars 20m in cash and an unspecified am-ount in
industrial equipment for the new facility which is to be set up with an
Argentine group. The factory will build commercial vehicles for the local
market and for export to Brazil to compensate for rising imports from Brazil
where GM has a major presence.
GM is joining forces with the local owners of Iveco, the Italian truck
company. In Argentina, Fiat holds only 30 per cent of Iveco. GM will set up
a joint venture with the wealthy Garfunkel family, which holds the other 70
per cent. Fiat is not expected to put more money into the venture, thus
reducing its holding in Iveco.
GM's decision follows the announcement last month by Renault, the French
state-owned car maker, to withdraw from Argentina by selling a majority
stake in its local subsidiary to a group of Argentine and Brazilian
investors.
