<HEADLINE>
FT  02 SEP 92 / Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACTIVITY IN the derivatives markets was said by dealers to have been the
quietest for many months, with many trading houses running on half their
normal staffing levels after the long August bank holiday weekend, writes
Steve Thompson.
The Footsie future opened at 2,311 but saw no business at that level and
soon moved up to touch 2,316 before sliding back to the day's low point of
2,293 just after lunch. It rallied to end the session at 2,303. Turnover in
the future was a miserable 5,429 lots.
In the traded options market, total volume reached 15,060 contracts. The
FT-SE 100 option attracted 6,424 deals, with one leading agency broker said
to have sold 500 September 2,300 puts. One of the independent traders
crossed 1,750 June 2,500 calls.
James Capel was said to have carried out two exceptionally large trades in
British Aerospace options just before the close of trading, with the
majority of the business in the November 200 puts and 220 calls.
The final turnover in Aerospace options came to 2,465 contracts, making it
the most heavily traded stock option. GEC was featured by a seller of 900
November 240 contracts at 210p.
